		<a href="US_Show.asp?id=80308">
		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/profile.gif" border="0" alt="Click Here to See the Profile for Beng Solarisan" width="22" height="11"></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
		
		<a href="MSG_MailBox.asp?mode=new&amp;sendto=Beng+Solarisan">
		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/privatemsg.gif" border="0" alt="Click Here to Message Beng Solarisan" width="22" height="11"></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
		
		<a href="MB_editmsg.asp?FID=67&FN=Paladin&SID=7&SN=EverQuest&TID=1453488&TN=Group+Leaders&CAT=Classes&SURL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww%2Eeverlore%2Ecom&MSID=1455196&PL=4">
		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/edit.gif" border="0" alt="Edit/Delete Message" width="18" height="13"></a>
		
		</font>
		<hr size="1">I basically have the same view, Kohi. I have yet to actually lead a big raid, the most I've ever led is about 18-20 people tops, but I like strict raid leaders. I think for a good raid to be successful to me, everything must be efficient and disciplined. Unfortunately from my experience, such a scenario is rare due to human nature and unpredictable flukes.</P><P>I think a raid leader should be mentally prepared well in advance to a raid because chances are you'll have to put up with crap from some players. He or she should also be wary of everyone's mood..if everyone starts to become bored or fussy, the chances of success drop. Morale is something a lot of people don't take account for. I also believe a raid leader should be aware if he or she is taking things too fast or too slow.</P><P>As for group leaders, I believe they should be aware of the same things but on a smaller scale. To me, when I lead a group, they become my responsibility. It's important for me to communicate efficiently and make sure everyone knows their roles. When a retreat is necessary, I try to make sure everyone is safe before I retreat. Pretty much for me it's expect from others as you expect from yourself.</P><P>I'm not in a large powerful guild, so I can only get to go on the better raids by invitation. I'm in a smaller guild by choice because the one I'm in is kinda like a teaching guild for levels between 20 and 40. When I go to raids such as Naggy, Vox, or raids I get invited to, I pay close attention to what the raid leader and group leaders are doing. I pretty much pick apart everything that goes on, from their actions to their attitudes from the beginning of the raid to the end. I take everything that I learn and teach it to those too low in hopes that people can have smarter people in the future.</P><P>Hehe..that's enough serious talking from me for now. Letting our dark "friends" understand how my mind works can prove to be a tactical disadvantage in the long run.</P><P>"In the darkest hours, Love shall always prevail."</P><P>Beng Solarisan<BR>Calvalier of the 51st Romance<BR>Kings of Disciples<BR>Xev<br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
	</font>
