		<hr size="1">Interesting stuff.  I talked to my Dad a bit about it today because its been on my mind and I was wondering how the military do it.  He's a retired Wing Commander.  He laughed an pointed to the USMC policy of there being only three responses to any given command: "yes sir", "no sir", and "sir - I do not understand".  I think this is very true in a raid situation.</P><P>While in a commercial environment it might make more efficient sense to ask who is NOT ready, in a mitigation sense it is better to ask who is ready and get a complete reply.  Asking who is NOT could have disasterous repercussions if someone missed the request and simply did not answer the question, when in fact the cleric was oom, or the mezzer was LD.</P><P>By the way Beng, I strongly recommend gaining some experience leading raids as soon as you can.  At higher levels the good raid leaders are invaluable.  I'm a bit late in life to be learning all this stuff but I am with a good guild who are willing to provide opportunties to learn because I asked to do so.  Expect me to be tossing ideas around here in the upcoming little while.</P><P>Also, I want to make Ring of Fire raids my specialty so if you have any advice about how to work that one efficiently I would appreciate hearing from you.</P><P><img src="http://homepages.paradise.net.nz/vikkibri/NDKohi.JPG" width=90 align=left><font face="Castellar,CenturySchoolbook,Arial" size="+1" color="CornflowerBlue"><b>Be strong<BR>Walk tall<BR>Go with pride</b></font><BR><a HREF="http://www.serenity-within.com/View_Member.php?Name=Kohinoor">Kohinoor Noblespirit of Felwithe</a><BR><a HREF="http://www.serenity-within.com">Serenity Within Guild</a></P><P>55th Crusade</P><P><a HREF="http://www.purenz.com/?98B94218-FEC9-430A-8CEF-AB2A52EAFCE1">New Zealand, home of Middle-Earth</a></font></P><P>Message edited by: Kohinoor (4/8/2002 4:30:51 AM)<br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
