		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/edit.gif" border="0" alt="Edit/Delete Message" width="18" height="13"></a>
		
		</font>
		<hr size="1">I think the parallel between a large-scale raid and the military is a very valid one.</P><P>When I'm leading a raid, I want it to run with military precision. When I ask a question, I expect it to be answered promptly and specifically, lag notwithstanding.</P><P>I expect all of my group leaders and raid participants to give me 201% attention during the raid.</P><P>Harsh, but I don't want the raid failing because some chanter decided they wanted to have cybersex with the cute wood elf druid sitting next to them and didn't mez the local that popped.</P><P>When I'm a group leader, or raid member, I try my best to act the way that I would want others to act when I am leading. If I'm raiding, don't send me a non-raid related tell other than 'Hey there.' Don't expect me to answer other than 'Hi, I'm raiding, I'll get back to you.'</P><P>I pick my group leaders based on two things.</P><P>They are either:</P><P>a) Not especially bright but follow orders correctly and to the letter, and promptly. They listen when I give an order, and when I say 'frog' they say 'how high?'</P><P>or (and this is far more preferable, but also far more rare)</P><P>b) They are smart, demonstrate intuition and self-motication, but also know how to follow orders promptly, and they trust me and my judgement on the situation.</P><P>I think what people don't understand is that leading a raid is not fun. You lead, organize and plan a raid for *everyone else*. You don't do it for yourself. You do it so the guild (or people involved) can have a little fun away from grinding, and maybe pick up some nice items for themselves.</P><P>Raid leaders rarely have any fun. You get a nice sense of satisfaction after the raid, assuming it was successful, but during the raid you're usually too busy coordinating, planning and making spot-decisions to notice any fun you may or may not be having.</P><P>People who mess about on raids are generally those who have not led them and don't know how much of a hassle it is.</P><P>Maybe it works both ways. To be a good leader, you've had to have had to be a good follower - But to be a good follower, maybe you've had to have had to be a good leader, too.</P><P><BR>--<BR>Rafal B'Fereign, Bard of the 30th Song<BR><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=78104" target=_new">Tarsk Longstrider</a>, Champion of the Wolves o' the North<BR>Xev</P><P>"You can't have everything. Where would you put it?"<br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
	</font>
	</td>
