		<hr size="1">I've found that the best raid leaders are people who can turn into nasty SOB's.  Don't take this the wrong way.</P><P>Most of the best raid leaders are nice, helpful, and good humored people.  But, once the raid starts, if you don't listen they WILL shout out what you did wrong, they WON'T tolerate people having side conversations, and so-help-you if you add "peanut gallery" remarks during the raid AFTER the strategy has been decided.  </P><P>Usually these people don't have to put on their "drill sergent" faces; they are good raid leaders because they surround themselves with competant people who know their roles very well and make sure people who aren't experienced with the raid leader know what is expected.  </P><P>So its not that good raid leaders are mean, its just that they have expectations, and if you don't feel like following the rules, then they have no problem "getting mean."</P><P>On the flip side, bad raid leadership, I'll give an example.  On a vox raid I recently went on, the two leaders weren't particularly assertive.  The raid was a public raid, so I can't exaclty blame them, the people there didn't particularly have a common group or kinship to fight for/with.  We defeated Vox, but only due to pure numbers, we had about 40 people.  Still, we took about 15 casualties, and had the group been more united and perhaps been better disiplined, we may have only had 2 or three casualties.</P><P>Simerro<BR>48th Level Paladin of Brell<BR>Wielder of Ghoulbane and Soulfire<BR>Innoruuk Server</P><P>"O, it is excellent to have a giants strength, but it is tyrannous to use it like a giant"<br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
